The marking scheme for the interviews is rather fair and the oldest candidates are somehow favoured by this. The rationale is that they have spent longer time tarmacking than the fresh graduates. The result is that a teacher may begin work at the ripe age of 35 years.
This is not good at all, but the whole country has serious unemployment problems, which may not be solved in a while to come.
Of late, it is getting ghastly. What happens is that locals in the surrounding schools feel that their ‘people’ should get these jobs and not the competing ‘outsiders’. Picture a situation where 4,000 people have applied for a post of teacher of English and Literature in a certain school.
There are local graduates there with the required qualifications, but are flooded with the other thousands from God knows where, who surely will be more qualified than them.



