Local politics
This is where local politics and tribalism takes centre stage. The machinations are done in the dark of the night and on the morning of the interviews, irate locals attack the ‘foreign’ candidates with whips, causing panic and running. The injuries will deter many of the thousands, thus increase the chances of their own taking up the job.
This crude method has now been applied in three counties and soon it shall spread elsewhere. Poor teachers are chased away like dogs and whipped in their backs mercilessly, simply because they wish to secure employment. This primitivity is new and if not checked now before it grows malignant, will soon become the norm.
The second disadvantage with it is the politics of delocalised teachers. They, too, shall not sit comfortable where the locals simply do not want them.
Those teachers employed in the 1980s and 1990s may not know what the younger generation is going through. Teaching was a calling for them and they chose it. It has become something else these days and the future is getting even scarier.
The commission must come up with new recruitment strategy that shall stop this practice, as well as remain fair and above board. It will be a very good thing for the profession, which is becoming something else and not worth being referred to as a calling.



